00:31:54.920 --> 00:32:00.770
As has been said, you
live your life forwards

00:32:00.770 --> 00:32:03.260
but you understand it backwards.

00:32:03.260 --> 00:32:06.070
And so it is for me.

00:32:06.070 --> 00:32:07.520
All my life, I have tried

00:32:07.520 --> 00:32:12.230
to understand the child-parent
dynamic of my life.

00:32:12.230 --> 00:32:14.190
My parents were deaf.

00:32:14.190 --> 00:32:16.390
I was their firstborn child.

00:32:16.390 --> 00:32:20.540
I could hear, and that has
made all the difference.

00:32:20.540 --> 00:32:25.840
It was 1933, the absolute bottom of
the great depression and the height

00:32:25.840 --> 00:32:30.860 position:56%
of the bad old days when the deaf in
America were treated by the hearing

00:32:30.860 --> 00:32:34.320
as somehow deficient, illiterate,

00:32:34.320 --> 00:32:37.580
largely incapable of
self-sufficiency.

00:32:37.580 --> 00:32:41.270
And as I witness everyday
of my childhood,

00:32:41.270 --> 00:32:44.920
objects of scorn and often pity.

00:32:44.920 --> 00:32:49.060
In my childhood some 80 years
ago, the hearing never tried

00:32:49.060 --> 00:32:55.270 position:56%
to understand or recognize or accept
my deaf mother and father as equals,

00:32:55.270 --> 00:32:59.510
capable as were they of
raising two children.

00:32:59.510 --> 00:33:03.130
And they often in my presence
expressed their incredulity

00:33:03.130 --> 00:33:08.270
by their distaste of the beautiful
expressive gestural language

00:33:08.270 --> 00:33:13.900
of the deaf, my first
language, as mere monkey talk.

00:33:13.900 --> 00:33:18.670
We had no telephone, no
car, there was no TV,

00:33:18.670 --> 00:33:21.860
let alone all the electronic
communicative devices

00:33:21.860 --> 00:33:23.290
that exist today.

00:33:23.290 --> 00:33:25.200
Thus, we were isolated.

00:33:25.200 --> 00:33:28.040
In plain sight but ignored.

00:33:28.040 --> 00:33:32.930
Within the larger hearing culture
of the apartment house we lived in

00:33:32.930 --> 00:33:37.210
and the block we lived on and
the neighborhood we lived within.

00:33:37.210 --> 00:33:41.520
The closest deaf family
live five miles away.

00:33:41.520 --> 00:33:45.990
I felt as a child as an
immigrant minefield with one foot

00:33:45.990 --> 00:33:49.740
in the old country of their birth
and the other foot in the country

00:33:49.740 --> 00:33:55.460 position:56%
and society and culture of the new
country that they had immigrated to.

00:33:55.460 --> 00:33:59.310
Never for a minute did I feel
as a child that I had succeeded

00:33:59.310 --> 00:34:04.240
in integrating the two vastly
different worlds I lived in,

00:34:04.240 --> 00:34:10.250
the one of silence, thoughtfulness
and touch that expressed love.

00:34:10.250 --> 00:34:15.790
And the other of incredible noise
and hustle and bustle with no time

00:34:15.790 --> 00:34:18.990
for physical displays of emotion.

00:34:18.990 --> 00:34:22.470
The one of speaking with
hands and face and body,

00:34:22.470 --> 00:34:25.730
a language that demands
total attention.

00:34:25.730 --> 00:34:28.440
A beautiful visual
language perceived

00:34:28.440 --> 00:34:31.230
and appreciated through my eyes.

00:34:31.230 --> 00:34:35.940
The other, spoken casually as if
I had overheard a conversation,

00:34:35.940 --> 00:34:38.970
with little or no thought
or expression or emotion,

00:34:38.970 --> 00:34:41.830
merely a tool for communication.

00:34:41.830 --> 00:34:45.410
And so I live and grew
and accommodated myself

00:34:45.410 --> 00:34:48.110
to both worlds everyday of my life.

00:34:48.110 --> 00:34:52.790
Often confused, occasionally
maladjusted, frustrated,

00:34:52.790 --> 00:34:55.010
aching to explain to others,

00:34:55.010 --> 00:34:58.550
as well as to myself the
predicament I was in.

00:34:58.550 --> 00:35:02.980
Until one day I left
my deaf home forever.

00:35:02.980 --> 00:35:07.030
And all my questions unresolved
during my childhood were buried

00:35:07.030 --> 00:35:11.080
in the daily short term quest
to fit in, to find a career,

00:35:11.080 --> 00:35:15.930
a way of making my living,
finding a mate, starting a family.

00:35:15.930 --> 00:35:20.790
I did all that with varying degrees
of success and failure and one day,

00:35:20.790 --> 00:35:24.850
rather late in life, all
the questions returned.

00:35:24.850 --> 00:35:29.770
Now demanding to be addressed
and answered if possible.

00:35:29.770 --> 00:35:32.360
And so I began to write.

00:35:32.360 --> 00:35:34.150
I had a story to tell.

00:35:34.150 --> 00:35:39.040
A story I had lived, the story
of a unique culture that exist

00:35:39.040 --> 00:35:42.330 position:56%
in America largely ignored, isolated

00:35:42.330 --> 00:35:45.980
by the larger culture
within which it exist.

00:35:45.980 --> 00:35:51.620
The first book I wrote was
"Flying Over Brooklyn".

00:35:51.620 --> 00:35:55.480
I was new to this game of
literature and storytelling.

00:35:55.480 --> 00:35:57.310
So, somewhat unsure of myself,

00:35:57.310 --> 00:36:01.570
I approached my story
side ways and not head on.

00:36:01.570 --> 00:36:04.440
I would tell the tale
through metaphors,

00:36:04.440 --> 00:36:07.780
images, allegories and symbols.

00:36:07.780 --> 00:36:13.710
For example, never is it stated in
the story that the mother is deaf.

00:36:13.710 --> 00:36:18.600
Snow would equal silence
and silence deafness.

00:36:18.600 --> 00:36:22.910
The stillness of the vast snowfall
would muffle the boy's words

00:36:22.910 --> 00:36:27.120
to all harsh meaningless
distracting noise.

00:36:27.120 --> 00:36:30.390
The remaining senses
would be magnified.

00:36:30.390 --> 00:36:34.110
The story is told through
the hearing boy's eyes.

00:36:34.110 --> 00:36:37.680
Eyes that see everything acutely.

00:36:37.680 --> 00:36:41.960
Nothing escapes his sight and
everything he sees has meaning.

00:36:41.960 --> 00:36:43.310
I quote from the book.

00:36:43.310 --> 00:36:47.530
I could see the parachute jump
and the giant wonder wheel.

00:36:47.530 --> 00:36:52.500
Their sharp outlines now
softened by pillows of snow.

00:36:52.500 --> 00:36:57.150
He smells the smell of roasted
peanuts and fat hotdogs.

00:36:57.150 --> 00:37:02.710
He taste the sticky sweetness of
cotton candy melting in his mouth.

00:37:02.710 --> 00:37:08.310
And he touches, he feels the
snowflakes melting on his cheeks

00:37:08.310 --> 00:37:10.700
and the wind on his face.

00:37:10.700 --> 00:37:12.470
The boy can fly.

00:37:12.470 --> 00:37:14.530
He flies over everything.

00:37:14.530 --> 00:37:17.330
He's above it all,
forever an observer.

00:37:17.330 --> 00:37:21.580
Aware of, but not really a
part of his everyday world.

00:37:21.580 --> 00:37:26.920
And in the end, his mother
awakens him from his dream.

00:37:26.920 --> 00:37:31.800
And in the last illustration
views the deep vast snow.

00:37:31.800 --> 00:37:35.320 position:56%
The essence of deafness with her arm

00:37:35.320 --> 00:37:39.110
around the boy's shoulders,
they are connected.

00:37:39.110 --> 00:37:43.730
They are co-joined, the deaf
mother and her hearing child

00:37:43.730 --> 00:37:46.130
through the love they
have for each other.

00:37:46.130 --> 00:37:52.530
A love that overrides while
combining all the senses.

00:37:52.530 --> 00:37:58.160 position:56%
With my current book, my latest book
published by Peachtree Publishers,

00:37:58.160 --> 00:38:03.490
titled "The Sound of All Things",
I begin the quarter of books,

00:38:03.490 --> 00:38:06.940
which subject is the
perceptions of a hearing boy

00:38:06.940 --> 00:38:12.460 position:56%
and his beloved deaf mother and
father who live in a world of sound.

00:38:12.460 --> 00:38:15.690
The dynamic of the hearing
child and his deaf parents

00:38:15.690 --> 00:38:18.590
in a time now long
gone when the hearing

00:38:18.590 --> 00:38:23.360
and deaf worlds were too
parallel but separate worlds.

00:38:23.360 --> 00:38:26.790
In "The Sound of All Things",
the boy is six years old.

00:38:26.790 --> 00:38:29.920
As long as he can remember,
the central fact of his life is

00:38:29.920 --> 00:38:33.420
that his mother and father
cannot hear him nor can they hear

00:38:33.420 --> 00:38:34.720
anything else.

00:38:34.720 --> 00:38:36.020
They are deaf.

00:38:36.020 --> 00:38:38.080
His deaf father tries to compensate

00:38:38.080 --> 00:38:42.450
by using his remaining
senses to perceive sound.

00:38:42.450 --> 00:38:46.170
At Coney Island, during a
fireworks display, while--

00:38:46.170 --> 00:38:47.760
and I quote from the book.

00:38:47.760 --> 00:38:52.990
The air was full of buzzing,
whistling, popping and screeching.

00:38:52.990 --> 00:38:57.100
The lights and colors danced
across my father's face.

00:38:57.100 --> 00:39:04.420 position:56%
He held out his hands sniffing the
air as if to see and taste and touch

00:39:04.420 --> 00:39:09.780
and smell the sounds of the
fireworks he couldn't hear.

00:39:09.780 --> 00:39:13.150
This was normal for the boy,
and up until the age of six,

00:39:13.150 --> 00:39:15.740 position:56%
he gave the fact no special meaning.

00:39:15.740 --> 00:39:19.150
But at the age of six,
his deaf father tasks him

00:39:19.150 --> 00:39:22.740
to be his interface
with the hearing world.

00:39:22.740 --> 00:39:26.000
He wants his son to be his ears.

00:39:26.000 --> 00:39:28.840
"What do you hear,"
my father asked me.

00:39:28.840 --> 00:39:31.710
"What does the ocean sound like?"

00:39:31.710 --> 00:39:34.620
A big job for a small boy.

00:39:34.620 --> 00:39:36.730
Overnight the roles reversed.

00:39:36.730 --> 00:39:40.410
Now, in a way, while they
are out in the hearing world,

00:39:40.410 --> 00:39:43.890
the boy is father to the man.

00:39:43.890 --> 00:39:48.440
This was common back then
before TV and closed captioning,

00:39:48.440 --> 00:39:54.120
movies with subtitle, emails,
instant messaging, short messaging,

00:39:54.120 --> 00:40:00.770
TTY, computers, Google, iPhones,
texting, tweeting, fax machines,

00:40:00.770 --> 00:40:05.610
and the portability of
iPads, FaceTime and Skype.

00:40:05.610 --> 00:40:08.170
None of that existed then.

00:40:08.170 --> 00:40:11.850 position:56%
This book just published, "The Sound
of All Things", begins my story.

00:40:11.850 --> 00:40:15.880
It is the foundation of every
book of mine that follows.

00:40:15.880 --> 00:40:22.780
In the next book, "The Printer",
the boy is now 10 years old.

00:40:22.780 --> 00:40:28.370
His father makes paper hats for
him when he comes home from work.

00:40:28.370 --> 00:40:30.300
The boy is proud of his father.

00:40:30.300 --> 00:40:32.630
His father has a job, a good job.

00:40:32.630 --> 00:40:37.920 position:56%
And he goes to work in a suit, a
shirt and a tie, and he wears a hat.

00:40:37.920 --> 00:40:41.070
But why do the neighbors
feel sorry for him?

00:40:41.070 --> 00:40:44.660
His father works for the New York
Daily News, the largest newspaper

00:40:44.660 --> 00:40:47.580
in the world at the
time of the story.

00:40:47.580 --> 00:40:50.340
They print two and a half
million copies a day,

00:40:50.340 --> 00:40:52.070
five million on Sunday.

00:40:52.070 --> 00:40:55.400
He's a printer, a compositor,
a good job.

00:40:55.400 --> 00:40:58.780
He's proud to have that
he works with language.

00:40:58.780 --> 00:41:00.630
He creates language with his hands.

00:41:00.630 --> 00:41:03.980
He's a typesetter, a skill
he learned at Fanwood,

00:41:03.980 --> 00:41:06.770
his deaf residential school.

00:41:06.770 --> 00:41:10.630 position:56%
The backstory is that the father
tells the boy how he first was taken

00:41:10.630 --> 00:41:15.150
to school by his father
and left there.

00:41:15.150 --> 00:41:19.380
The first day, he felt
abandoned and he cried.

00:41:19.380 --> 00:41:23.470
But he soon realized that rather
than being lost, he had been found.

00:41:23.470 --> 00:41:28.360
He now lived in a familiar world,
populated by boys who were just

00:41:28.360 --> 00:41:33.540
like him, no longer that he
feel different and alone.

00:41:33.540 --> 00:41:36.500
At night in the communal
bathroom, he learned the language

00:41:36.500 --> 00:41:39.740
from the older boys, the
beautiful language of the deaf,

00:41:39.740 --> 00:41:44.920
a gesture language of signs,
utilizing hands, face and body.

00:41:44.920 --> 00:41:47.310 position:56%
During the day, he learned to trade.

00:41:47.310 --> 00:41:52.240
Most of the deaf boys learned
shoe repair or house painting.

00:41:52.240 --> 00:41:54.050
He learned typesetting.

00:41:54.050 --> 00:41:59.870 position:56%
As a boy, I write, my father
learned how to speak with his hands.

00:41:59.870 --> 00:42:02.900
As a man, he learned how to turn--

00:42:02.900 --> 00:42:07.130
type letters into words
and sentences.

00:42:07.130 --> 00:42:10.480
My father loved being a printer.

00:42:10.480 --> 00:42:13.040
One day, the deaf father
takes his son on the subway

00:42:13.040 --> 00:42:14.340
to the place where he works.

00:42:14.340 --> 00:42:18.880
And now, the boy learns of the
reality of the workplace prejudice

00:42:18.880 --> 00:42:23.150
that his father endures
every single day.

00:42:23.150 --> 00:42:27.100
Quoting the book, sometimes
my father felt sad

00:42:27.100 --> 00:42:31.800
about the way he was treated by
his fellow workers who could hear.

00:42:31.800 --> 00:42:34.120
Because they could talk
to him with their hands,

00:42:34.120 --> 00:42:38.070
they seemed to ignore him-- I mean,
because they couldn't talk to him,

00:42:38.070 --> 00:42:39.790
they seemed to ignore him.

00:42:39.790 --> 00:42:44.980
Years went by as my father and
the hearing worked side by side,

00:42:44.980 --> 00:42:49.010
they never exchanged
a single thought.

00:42:49.010 --> 00:42:51.170
On the subway ride back home,

00:42:51.170 --> 00:42:55.340
he sees a deaf man selling
deaf alphabet cards.

00:42:55.340 --> 00:42:57.220
His father is angry.

00:42:57.220 --> 00:43:01.990
He yells in sign languages
into the deaf man.

00:43:01.990 --> 00:43:03.470
The deaf man runs away,

00:43:03.470 --> 00:43:08.000
and the entire subways
caused steer-- stares at us.

00:43:08.000 --> 00:43:10.310
Be self-sufficient, the
father tells the boy.

00:43:10.310 --> 00:43:13.670
Being deaf does not rob
a man of his dignity.

00:43:13.670 --> 00:43:19.160 position:56%
Being deaf does not define a person,
who they are or what they do,

00:43:19.160 --> 00:43:22.750
how they live is what's important,
the father tells the boy.

00:43:22.750 --> 00:43:26.530
The boy hardly understands what
the father is saying to him.

00:43:26.530 --> 00:43:31.150
The signs pour from his father's
hands in a time of motion

00:43:31.150 --> 00:43:33.600
and meaning, too hard to follow.

00:43:33.600 --> 00:43:39.410
But the boy instinctively feels
his father's strength, his manhood,

00:43:39.410 --> 00:43:44.220
his pride and above all,
his love for his son.

00:43:44.220 --> 00:43:48.970
My next book, "Dad, Jackie
and Me", which has won many--

00:43:48.970 --> 00:43:56.960 position:56%
I'm happy to say, many, many
awards, the boy is now 13 years old.

00:43:56.960 --> 00:43:59.440
For his birthday, his father
buys a pair of tickets

00:43:59.440 --> 00:44:02.020
to the Brooklyn Dodger
baseball game at Ebbets Field

00:44:02.020 --> 00:44:05.550
to see the first black
baseball player

00:44:05.550 --> 00:44:09.220
in Major League Baseball,
Jackie Robinson.

00:44:09.220 --> 00:44:12.940
The father identifies with
Robinson, a black man,

00:44:12.940 --> 00:44:15.760
but the boy has no idea why.

00:44:15.760 --> 00:44:18.890
The father never played
sports at his deaf school.

00:44:18.890 --> 00:44:22.060
The emphasis was on learning
how to make a living,

00:44:22.060 --> 00:44:24.310
and not how to play games.

00:44:24.310 --> 00:44:26.820
At Ebbets Field, the boy
experiences prejudice

00:44:26.820 --> 00:44:29.640
and discrimination
on a larger scale.

00:44:29.640 --> 00:44:34.040
It seems to him that the entire
baseball world hates Jackie

00:44:34.040 --> 00:44:37.050
Robinson, but they
don't even know him.

00:44:37.050 --> 00:44:41.590
And the boy realized, it doesn't
matter, Robinson is black,

00:44:41.590 --> 00:44:45.570
and having black skin is reason
enough for some people to hate him,

00:44:45.570 --> 00:44:48.380
just like it seems to the boy

00:44:48.380 --> 00:44:55.230
that some people hate his father
mostly because he cannot hear.

00:44:55.230 --> 00:44:59.260
Now, he understands why his father
identifies with Jackie Robinson.

00:44:59.260 --> 00:45:02.910
And the boy notes how some
people stare at his father

00:45:02.910 --> 00:45:07.600
as he cheers Jackie
on in his deaf voice,

00:45:07.600 --> 00:45:10.840
many with distaste on their face.

00:45:10.840 --> 00:45:15.650
By the way, please note, the
new Ken Burns documentary film

00:45:15.650 --> 00:45:20.350
about Jackie Robinson in
which I get to tell my story

00:45:20.350 --> 00:45:24.540
about my deaf father and Jackie
Robinson and the book I wrote

00:45:24.540 --> 00:45:30.780
about the two of them will premiere
this coming Monday on April 11th

00:45:30.780 --> 00:45:33.700
on Public Broadcasting Channel.

00:45:33.700 --> 00:45:37.680
The date and the time will be
announced in your local newspaper.

00:45:37.680 --> 00:45:38.980
It's worth watching,

00:45:38.980 --> 00:45:41.790
it's a tremendous movie
about Jackie Robinson.

00:45:41.790 --> 00:45:46.170
As I say, I get to act out a little
bit of it in telling the story

00:45:46.170 --> 00:45:48.240
which I love, which is my story.

00:45:48.240 --> 00:45:50.790
The next book in this
story, "Hands of My Father",

00:45:50.790 --> 00:45:53.140
which I don't have a copy with me.

00:45:53.140 --> 00:45:57.790
I am absolutely proud to
advise you that this book,

00:45:57.790 --> 00:46:03.130
"Hands of My Father", was chosen
by the Library of Congress

00:46:03.130 --> 00:46:06.640
to be recorded as an
audible book for the blind.

00:46:06.640 --> 00:46:08.830
They don't do that with
every book, but they did it

00:46:08.830 --> 00:46:11.770
with my memoir, "Hands
of My Father".

00:46:11.770 --> 00:46:16.460
This is a book, a memoir,
for all ages, any age.

00:46:16.460 --> 00:46:20.930
It attempts through the eyes and
sensibility of one hearing child

00:46:20.930 --> 00:46:24.000
to tell the story of his
deaf parents who were born

00:46:24.000 --> 00:46:27.290
at the turn of the last century.

00:46:27.290 --> 00:46:30.500
The firstborn in each
of their families

00:46:30.500 --> 00:46:32.690
to hearing immigrant parents

00:46:32.690 --> 00:46:36.610
who barely knew the
English language themselves

00:46:36.610 --> 00:46:42.390
and never learned a
single word of sign.

00:46:42.390 --> 00:46:46.420 position:56%
They met in a place called Brooklyn,
a place that no longer exists.

00:46:46.420 --> 00:46:51.460
It was then more rural, a series
of villages than an actual city,

00:46:51.460 --> 00:46:57.570
in old Coney Island, the poor man's
Miami Beach, and they fell in love.

00:46:57.570 --> 00:47:01.800
They found in each other their
mirror image, partners for life,

00:47:01.800 --> 00:47:05.770
defenders of each other,
taking refuge in each other

00:47:05.770 --> 00:47:09.160
in an often hostile hearing world.

00:47:09.160 --> 00:47:11.670
They were now complete.

00:47:11.670 --> 00:47:15.280
And then, against their
parents' well-intended

00:47:15.280 --> 00:47:21.090
but heartless admonition that
they were children themselves,

00:47:21.090 --> 00:47:27.170 position:56%
they ignored their parents and they
dared to have a child who they loved

00:47:27.170 --> 00:47:31.350
as they loved each other,
but who because he could hear

00:47:31.350 --> 00:47:34.860
and they could not never
could be fully a part of them.

00:47:34.860 --> 00:47:38.640
And now, they found
themselves in a unique world,

00:47:38.640 --> 00:47:43.930
sandwiched between their hearing
parents and their hearing child.

00:47:43.930 --> 00:47:48.800
The bridge in both directions
was for these two special people,

00:47:48.800 --> 00:47:52.340
their infinite capacity for love.

00:47:52.340 --> 00:47:56.270
But as is the case with race today,
much has changed for the deaf.

00:47:56.270 --> 00:47:59.360
And yet, much remains the same.

00:47:59.360 --> 00:48:02.280
You're all aware of the
changes primarily ADA,

00:48:02.280 --> 00:48:04.850
Americans with Disability
Act, the amazing array

00:48:04.850 --> 00:48:08.660
of electronic communicative
devices and platforms.

00:48:08.660 --> 00:48:13.450
But in human terms, in human
interaction with the hearing world,

00:48:13.450 --> 00:48:18.120
I've seen this, we all
have, much remains the same.

00:48:18.120 --> 00:48:21.340
I learned just how little has
changed when I brought my mother

00:48:21.340 --> 00:48:25.240
to live with me when she
turned 89 and broke her pelvis

00:48:25.240 --> 00:48:27.480
and then had a series of strokes.

00:48:27.480 --> 00:48:31.550
Soon upon arriving in my home,
she fell and broke her hip.

00:48:31.550 --> 00:48:35.590
In time, her pelvis healed and
she survived a hip replacement.

00:48:35.590 --> 00:48:38.470
But now, she was confined
to a wheelchair.

00:48:38.470 --> 00:48:43.800 position:56%
For the next six years, I witnessed
a series of events that hearken back

00:48:43.800 --> 00:48:48.890
to the '30s and '40s, a time
of no sympathy for the deaf

00:48:48.890 --> 00:48:52.650
or accommodation for the
deaf, to mention a few,

00:48:52.650 --> 00:48:54.610
hospitals, doctors, nurses.

00:48:54.610 --> 00:48:58.890
In the emergency room which you
all too often found yourself,

00:48:58.890 --> 00:49:04.950
there was a sign regarding the
availability of an interpreter,

00:49:04.950 --> 00:49:07.350
but there was no interpreter.

00:49:07.350 --> 00:49:11.940
And when I pointed that out to
the staff, they looked at me.

00:49:11.940 --> 00:49:14.790
I pointed out the sign that
was sitting in plain sight

00:49:14.790 --> 00:49:18.250
at the admission desk,
they never noticed it,

00:49:18.250 --> 00:49:21.270
they never didn't know
what an interpreter was.

00:49:21.270 --> 00:49:24.610
They weren't aware of the
sign and what it called for.

00:49:24.610 --> 00:49:26.240
Her doctors not aware of--

00:49:26.240 --> 00:49:30.550
by law that now, he had
to have an interpreter,

00:49:30.550 --> 00:49:34.790
were rendered virtually useless
in diagnosing and communicating.

00:49:34.790 --> 00:49:39.050
They simply had no
time for a deaf person.

00:49:39.050 --> 00:49:42.170
Her nurses, that was
the best of all.

00:49:42.170 --> 00:49:48.310
Upon admission, I advised the
nurse's station, my mother is deaf.

00:49:48.310 --> 00:49:54.060
Next morning above her bed
was a large handwritten sign,

00:49:54.060 --> 00:49:57.250
patient is hard of hearing.

00:49:57.250 --> 00:50:01.600
I pointed out that hard
of hearing was not deaf

00:50:01.600 --> 00:50:04.620
and explained the difference.

00:50:04.620 --> 00:50:09.690
OK. Early the next morning,
I found a new sign in place

00:50:09.690 --> 00:50:12.770
above her bed, patient is deaf.

00:50:12.770 --> 00:50:17.900
I swear this is true,
patient is deaf, shout.

00:50:17.900 --> 00:50:22.550
Shout. And sure enough, while
I was in my mom's bedside,

00:50:22.550 --> 00:50:26.770
a nurse came in, saw the
sign and began to shout

00:50:26.770 --> 00:50:30.150
at my mother right in her face.

00:50:30.150 --> 00:50:35.160
On another-- This is not
1930, this is eight years ago.

00:50:35.160 --> 00:50:38.670
On another occasion, another
hospital visit, I came to a room

00:50:38.670 --> 00:50:43.600
at dawn and she was sleeping,
and her hands were tied

00:50:43.600 --> 00:50:47.570
to the bed railing
with strips of cloth.

00:50:47.570 --> 00:50:50.810
I raged at the nurses, raged,

00:50:50.810 --> 00:50:53.330
telling them that my
mother was deaf.

00:50:53.330 --> 00:50:58.360
And the deaf communicate with
their hands using sign language.

00:50:58.360 --> 00:51:01.860
One nurse was surprised,
your mother can talk?

00:51:01.860 --> 00:51:03.160
She asked.

00:51:03.160 --> 00:51:06.470
She didn't know that the
deaf had a language at all.

00:51:06.470 --> 00:51:09.790
Her hospital said no text,
telephone in the emergency room,

00:51:09.790 --> 00:51:12.940
the main library, anywhere--
or anywhere else I could find.

00:51:12.940 --> 00:51:14.390
What's the conclusion?

00:51:14.390 --> 00:51:18.630
Without me to interpret for
her in a medical setting,

00:51:18.630 --> 00:51:21.920
she would have been
virtually helpless.

00:51:21.920 --> 00:51:26.140
And for the general population,
the usual, stares, gaping mouths,

00:51:26.140 --> 00:51:29.980
reaction ranging from
pointedly ignoring my mother

00:51:29.980 --> 00:51:32.570
to overtly dismissing her.

00:51:32.570 --> 00:51:35.600
But there were some examples
of how nothing has changed

00:51:35.600 --> 00:51:38.790
that I experienced
that I have of my own.

00:51:38.790 --> 00:51:40.470
I'm not deaf.

00:51:40.470 --> 00:51:45.090
But ironically, I am now diagnosed
as being functionally deaf.

00:51:45.090 --> 00:51:47.570
As a child while growing
up, I would often wonder,

00:51:47.570 --> 00:51:49.510
what's it like to be deaf?

00:51:49.510 --> 00:51:53.540
I would close my eyes
and imagine being blind,

00:51:53.540 --> 00:51:57.040
but I couldn't close my
ears and imagine being deaf

00:51:57.040 --> 00:51:58.800
like my mother and father.

00:51:58.800 --> 00:52:01.390
Now, I don't have to
try to close my years,

00:52:01.390 --> 00:52:04.770 position:56%
time and age has taken care of that.

00:52:04.770 --> 00:52:08.320
Without my hearing aids, the
most powerful in the market,

00:52:08.320 --> 00:52:12.490
I would hear very little and
we can comprehend even less.

00:52:12.490 --> 00:52:15.780
But even with the aids, I have
trouble understanding speech,

00:52:15.780 --> 00:52:20.130
often getting things
wrong, sometimes comically.

00:52:20.130 --> 00:52:23.270
But strangers don't find
it funny when I asked them

00:52:23.270 --> 00:52:26.020
to please repeat themselves.

00:52:26.020 --> 00:52:30.420
Their reactions range from
impatience to outright hostility.

00:52:30.420 --> 00:52:33.170
What's the matter, you
stupid or something?

00:52:33.170 --> 00:52:35.940
With all of this firsthand
experience between the deaf

00:52:35.940 --> 00:52:39.160
and the hearing, with those
of my parents from the 1930s

00:52:39.160 --> 00:52:41.210
on through the new millennium,

00:52:41.210 --> 00:52:45.800
I'm convinced that the essential
problem is ignorance on the part

00:52:45.800 --> 00:52:47.600
of the majority of hearing people.

00:52:47.600 --> 00:52:50.110
And the heart of all
misunderstanding

00:52:50.110 --> 00:52:52.860
between human beings
is that ignorance.

00:52:52.860 --> 00:52:57.410
The more light we can shed on
this subject, deaf history,

00:52:57.410 --> 00:53:02.900
current deaf life in America,
deaf culture and ASL through books

00:53:02.900 --> 00:53:05.890
in libraries available to all,

00:53:05.890 --> 00:53:08.580
the better we can tell
