01:09:20.460 --> 01:09:26.400
that says that, "His
face was white and stern.

01:09:26.400 --> 01:09:28.490
The lines about his mouth were set

01:09:28.490 --> 01:09:32.940
and his eye expressed both
deep anger and sorrow."

01:09:32.940 --> 01:09:37.170
That quote really made me think,

01:09:37.170 --> 01:09:41.580
how was it that deaf people
lived during the civil war?

01:09:43.030 --> 01:09:49.100
I wondered what they did, how
they got involved in the war.

01:09:52.310 --> 01:09:53.960
Next slide please.

01:09:53.960 --> 01:10:03.950
So, I had the story of this one
deaf man and he was very involved

01:10:03.950 --> 01:10:05.360
in the war I should I say.

01:10:05.360 --> 01:10:09.450
He was an editorial
writer in his life.

01:10:09.450 --> 01:10:15.210
He had many hearing soldiers
in the war he corresponded with

01:10:15.210 --> 01:10:18.620
and he would publish
their stories in his--

01:10:18.620 --> 01:10:21.810
a newspaper from Anamosa., Iowa.

01:10:21.810 --> 01:10:26.090
He published their stories there
and really called them friends.

01:10:26.090 --> 01:10:29.420
He considered them
very close companions.

01:10:29.420 --> 01:10:32.330
But his life was threatened
several times because he fought

01:10:32.330 --> 01:10:38.150
with copperheads, you know, the
peace democrats at the time.

01:10:38.150 --> 01:10:41.130
He hated them, they hated him.

01:10:41.130 --> 01:10:45.060
On the streets, they would confront
each other and get in some scuffles

01:10:45.060 --> 01:10:47.710
and they would write
notes back and forth.

01:10:52.040 --> 01:10:56.790
And Edmund Booth's
daughter wrote that his--

01:10:56.790 --> 01:11:02.830
her father who was deaf
was-- had a very mighty pen,

01:11:02.830 --> 01:11:04.400
much mightier than the sword.

01:11:04.400 --> 01:11:09.310
And she felt that he
did more for the Union

01:11:09.310 --> 01:11:12.890
than any soldier potentially
had done rather

01:11:12.890 --> 01:11:17.050
than potentially the exception
of Grant Lee or Sheridan.

01:11:17.050 --> 01:11:20.670
So these newspapers
would copy his editorials

01:11:20.670 --> 01:11:23.520
and publish them across the nation.

01:11:29.720 --> 01:11:31.930
So, this raised the
question of, you know,

01:11:31.930 --> 01:11:34.990
I wanted to continue
my NIH research to see

01:11:34.990 --> 01:11:36.930
if there were more deaf
people that I could find

01:11:36.930 --> 01:11:38.230
who had been engaged in the war.

01:11:38.230 --> 01:11:43.500
I didn't really find
anything, any specific book

01:11:43.500 --> 01:11:47.090
that was the talked-about deaf
people's involvements in the war.

01:11:47.090 --> 01:11:52.610
I did briefly find a few articles
that mentioned a woman by the name

01:11:52.610 --> 01:11:57.110
of Laura Redden who had
written several things.

01:11:57.110 --> 01:12:00.260
I found one website that said
there had been no soldiers

01:12:00.260 --> 01:12:02.470
who were deaf in the civil war.

01:12:02.470 --> 01:12:07.340
But I was skeptical of that truth
and didn't accept it for my own.

01:12:07.340 --> 01:12:09.690
So, I continued my NIH research.

01:12:09.690 --> 01:12:13.800
And I felt like that was really
the only way to go about this,

01:12:13.800 --> 01:12:18.470
this journey to find who was deaf
and involved in the civil war.

01:12:18.470 --> 01:12:26.370
In the area of writing, you know,
fighting with the pen, if you will,

01:12:26.370 --> 01:12:31.850
I found that deaf writers
and deaf newspaper editors,

01:12:31.850 --> 01:12:35.280
deaf poets were somewhat prevalent.

01:12:35.280 --> 01:12:40.530
I found a deaf diarist as well.

01:12:40.530 --> 01:12:45.030
Deaf people corresponded with
each other in letter form.

01:12:45.030 --> 01:12:49.550
So, we were lucky to find a lot of
documentation about their thoughts

01:12:49.550 --> 01:12:52.660
and how it was that they
were believing in the cause

01:12:52.660 --> 01:12:59.400
of either the north or the
south through what they wrote.

01:12:59.400 --> 01:13:01.130
There's also fighting
with the sword.

01:13:01.130 --> 01:13:06.300
I found several stories
of deaf soldiers, many.

01:13:06.300 --> 01:13:15.250
Some of whom joined the north, some
of whom joined the south and some

01:13:15.250 --> 01:13:20.350
who fought and died, some who
weren't accepted into the army

01:13:20.350 --> 01:13:24.320
because of the medical
test that ruled them

01:13:24.320 --> 01:13:26.570
out where the doctors would refuse

01:13:26.570 --> 01:13:29.710
to admit profoundly deaf
people into the core.

01:13:29.710 --> 01:13:32.680
Although, they would often
accept hard of hearing people,

01:13:32.680 --> 01:13:39.310
but they would try to, you know,
limit them to saying that deaf--

01:13:39.310 --> 01:13:41.450
that hard of hearing
people wouldn't know

01:13:41.450 --> 01:13:44.220
from which side an
enemy was approaching.

01:13:44.220 --> 01:13:48.920 position:56%
And so, a lot of issues came up when
I was finding these deaf soldiers.

01:13:48.920 --> 01:13:51.390
And the theme was that hard

01:13:51.390 --> 01:13:56.800
of hearing soldiers were more
prevalent than deaf soldiers.

01:13:56.800 --> 01:14:01.040 position:56%
Among those who were accepted into
the armies, they were often assigned

01:14:01.040 --> 01:14:06.430
to noncombatant roles like
clerks or horse care or cooks

01:14:06.430 --> 01:14:11.380
and not many fought, although there
were some stories there as well.

01:14:11.380 --> 01:14:15.490
There were a lot of stories
about hearing men who became deaf

01:14:15.490 --> 01:14:20.840
as a result of their service in the
army, tens of thousands who fought

01:14:20.840 --> 01:14:24.130
and who through injuries
became deaf.

01:14:24.130 --> 01:14:26.730
And so, I think that that was
actually an interesting experience

01:14:26.730 --> 01:14:29.890
to read about because you could
see how they had to adjust

01:14:29.890 --> 01:14:32.740
to the deaf world,
but at the same time,

01:14:32.740 --> 01:14:35.340
fight for their own
lives and survival.

01:14:35.340 --> 01:14:38.960
So, I saw many experiences that
popped up through my research

01:14:38.960 --> 01:14:44.790
where these people who were
born hearing began to understand

01:14:44.790 --> 01:14:49.000
that there was this new balance in
their lives, that they were living

01:14:49.000 --> 01:14:54.530
with tinnitus or for those of
you who are deaf like myself,

01:14:54.530 --> 01:14:58.570
learning that vibrations
can mean something to you,

01:14:58.570 --> 01:15:02.410
like that there's a loud noise
somewhere, either far away

01:15:02.410 --> 01:15:06.580
or closer depending on the type
of vibrations that you feel.

01:15:06.580 --> 01:15:12.090
So, these people were learning to
gain these feels in their lives

01:15:12.090 --> 01:15:16.120
as a result of becoming deaf.

01:15:16.120 --> 01:15:19.980
And that, you know, eventually
would actually help them in battle

01:15:19.980 --> 01:15:21.420
if they decided to continue on.

01:15:21.420 --> 01:15:25.680 position:56%
I think the most interesting thing
for me was when the war was actually

01:15:25.680 --> 01:15:30.220
over and seeing the stories that
emerged there, seeing the tens

01:15:30.220 --> 01:15:32.830
of thousands of hearing
men who became deaf

01:15:32.830 --> 01:15:38.040
who did not receive pensions equal
to those who had other disabilities

01:15:38.040 --> 01:15:39.540
that they sustained during the war.

01:15:39.540 --> 01:15:44.670 position:56%
These men actually formed an
organization called the Silent Army.

01:15:44.670 --> 01:15:48.720
And the Silent Army fought
the United States government

01:15:48.720 --> 01:15:51.410
for equal pension pay as other--

01:15:51.410 --> 01:15:53.580
as people with other
types of disabilities.

01:15:53.580 --> 01:15:56.130
And we can actually thank the
Library of Congress for that

01:15:56.130 --> 01:15:59.060
because the Library of
Congress has a book in fact

01:15:59.060 --> 01:16:06.110
in its archives called "The Silent
Army" with 101 actual stories

01:16:06.110 --> 01:16:10.690
of people who became deaf
during the Civil War and later

01:16:10.690 --> 01:16:14.570
on could not get jobs because
of the attitudes that existed

01:16:14.570 --> 01:16:19.020
within hearing communities and
the new issues that cropped

01:16:19.020 --> 01:16:22.530
up around communication
with family and colleagues.

01:16:22.530 --> 01:16:30.560 position:56%
Some of you have who have-- who live
here may have visited Fort Defense--

01:16:30.560 --> 01:16:31.860
Fort Stevens rather.

01:16:31.860 --> 01:16:33.920
It's here in DC on Georgia Avenue.

01:16:33.920 --> 01:16:40.040
So if any of you have seen it,
you might be familiar with it.

01:16:40.040 --> 01:16:43.550 position:56%
For those of you who are not, Fort
Stevens has a very interesting story

01:16:43.550 --> 01:16:45.540 position:56%
that I'll share with you here today.

01:16:45.540 --> 01:16:49.230
I'll use a quote that I mentioned
before that some people--

01:16:49.230 --> 01:16:51.320 position:56%
some deaf people had joined militias

01:16:51.320 --> 01:16:55.810
because they couldn't actually
be accepted to the official army

01:16:55.810 --> 01:17:00.200
so they joined instead militia
organizations to protect the towns

01:17:00.200 --> 01:17:02.720
when the enemy combatants
were approaching.

01:17:02.720 --> 01:17:05.650
Sometimes the armies, you know,
weren't readily available.

01:17:05.650 --> 01:17:08.690
So, civilians had to fight
the wars for themselves.

01:17:08.690 --> 01:17:12.260
So, this is the story of
an 11-year-old deaf boy

01:17:12.260 --> 01:17:17.490
who was a gardener in
fact in his community

01:17:17.490 --> 01:17:22.290
with a woman whose husband
was an admiral in the US Navy,

01:17:22.290 --> 01:17:25.090
and she wrote letters to
her husband about this--

01:17:25.090 --> 01:17:30.190
about what was going
on in her hometown.

01:17:30.190 --> 01:17:33.410
And when the south was approaching
and attacking Washington, DC,

01:17:33.410 --> 01:17:37.020
Fort Stevens was the only battle

01:17:37.020 --> 01:17:41.390
that President Lincoln had
actually observed in person.

01:17:41.390 --> 01:17:45.550
So, he actually came to the area.

01:17:45.550 --> 01:17:48.320
The soldiers warned him that
he shouldn't stand up because

01:17:48.320 --> 01:17:52.980
as he was very tall, they were
worried that he would be a target.

01:17:52.980 --> 01:17:56.310
That was the only battle as I said

01:17:56.310 --> 01:17:59.030
that Lincoln was there
for in person.

01:17:59.030 --> 01:18:02.290
But at any rate, the soldiers
were there, they were talking

01:18:02.290 --> 01:18:04.360
about that the president was there.

01:18:04.360 --> 01:18:09.180
But they actually more talked
about this 11-year-old deaf boy

01:18:09.180 --> 01:18:13.290
who stole a rifle from the
woman that he was working

01:18:13.290 --> 01:18:18.940
as a gardener whose husband was
the admiral and joined the battle

01:18:18.940 --> 01:18:20.770
and killed six rebels
in the process.

01:18:20.770 --> 01:18:24.090
Can you imagine an
11-year-old deaf boy doing this?

01:18:24.090 --> 01:18:27.200
And I have-- Anyway, I have a quote
from her letter, that the woman

01:18:27.200 --> 01:18:30.500
that he was working for, to her
husband describing the situation.

01:18:30.500 --> 01:18:34.270
She says, "The soldiers say
that he killed some five

01:18:34.270 --> 01:18:36.620
or six Rebel sharpshooters.

01:18:36.620 --> 01:18:38.380
I do not like to think of anyone

01:18:38.380 --> 01:18:42.360
so young taking the
lives of so many men.

01:18:42.360 --> 01:18:47.170
But this young gardener
of mine is no common boy

01:18:47.170 --> 01:18:51.460
and has shown marked
character from infancy."

01:18:51.460 --> 01:18:58.020
So, there are other quotes that
document most of the story.

01:18:58.020 --> 01:19:02.290
And the book that I'm writing now
has about 200 stories in total

01:19:02.290 --> 01:19:05.910
that talk about deaf people's
involvements in the civil war,

01:19:05.910 --> 01:19:10.750
begets involvement with
pen or with the sword.

01:19:10.750 --> 01:19:17.940
I'm not sure if any of you have
read the fictional story called

01:19:17.940 --> 01:19:19.480
"Chickamauga".

01:19:19.480 --> 01:19:24.670
But this story is a
story about a young boy.

01:19:24.670 --> 01:19:31.200
And in the story, he
plays with a wood sword.

01:19:31.200 --> 01:19:32.620
He goes out into the woods.

01:19:32.620 --> 01:19:37.290
And during the battle
of Chickamauga,

01:19:37.290 --> 01:19:41.180
the deaf boy didn't hear the fact
that there was shooting going

01:19:41.180 --> 01:19:43.370
on around him, continued to play.

01:19:43.370 --> 01:19:48.280
But he started to see some wounded
and crippled soldiers down on hands

01:19:48.280 --> 01:19:51.530
and knees from their battle wounds.

01:19:51.530 --> 01:19:55.600
This young boy actually climbs
up and rides on one of the horses

01:19:55.600 --> 01:19:58.270
that had been-- with
one of the soldiers.

01:19:58.270 --> 01:20:02.210
And so at first you think,
goodness, this is so funny.

01:20:02.210 --> 01:20:04.460
This kid is so naïve to believe

01:20:04.460 --> 01:20:08.150
that the area is safe
despite what he sees.

01:20:08.150 --> 01:20:10.780
He actually ends up falling
asleep in the middle of the battle

01:20:10.780 --> 01:20:15.040
and wakes up to see a
light off in a distance.

01:20:15.040 --> 01:20:19.820
He follows it and finds that his
farmhouse has been burned down

01:20:19.820 --> 01:20:22.200
and he finds that his
mother is dead now.

01:20:22.200 --> 01:20:24.970
At the end of the story, it turns

01:20:24.970 --> 01:20:31.550
out that the child was a deaf
mute child as the story goes.

01:20:31.550 --> 01:20:35.940
A bit of a surprise ending for me,
I read that and thought to myself,

01:20:35.940 --> 01:20:40.900
it seems like this is one of a
very few stories that we can find

01:20:40.900 --> 01:20:43.970
of deaf children's experience
in the world-- in the war.

01:20:43.970 --> 01:20:48.810
And I think that it was interesting
that they would portray this child

01:20:48.810 --> 01:20:54.000
as naïve because we can
see throughout the stories

01:20:54.000 --> 01:20:56.580
that I've found that deaf children
have very much been involved

01:20:56.580 --> 01:20:58.580
in the war and all aspects of it.

01:20:58.580 --> 01:21:06.940 position:56%
In one school for the deaf, the deaf
children made 1.5 million bullets

01:21:06.940 --> 01:21:09.480
for the southern army.

01:21:09.480 --> 01:21:11.950
Now, if you would--
if you're a teacher,

01:21:11.950 --> 01:21:14.910
anyone here on the audience,

01:21:14.910 --> 01:21:16.950
I'm not sure that you
would allow deaf children

01:21:16.950 --> 01:21:18.290
to play with gunpowder.

01:21:18.290 --> 01:21:22.390
But this school for the
deaf supported their--

01:21:22.390 --> 01:21:27.710 position:56%
the southern army and they also
made confederate money as well there

01:21:27.710 --> 01:21:30.630
because they had a print
shop in the school.

01:21:30.630 --> 01:21:36.260
So, they were able to print
money for the southern states.

01:21:36.260 --> 01:21:41.130
They also made flags to support
their army depending on what--

01:21:41.130 --> 01:21:45.160
you know, where-- what states
these deaf schools were in.

01:21:45.160 --> 01:21:48.150
Some of the girls would be
assigned to sew up uniforms.

01:21:48.150 --> 01:21:50.580
The boys would be assigned
to make boots.

01:21:50.580 --> 01:21:54.160
And the kids in school wrote
about war time events as well.

01:21:54.160 --> 01:21:59.170
I just met somebody
from Kentucky here.

01:21:59.170 --> 01:22:05.200
I found that after the battle
of Berryville in Kentucky,

01:22:05.200 --> 01:22:06.610
there were hundreds and hundreds

01:22:06.610 --> 01:22:09.090
of dead bodies just
strewn about the field.

01:22:09.090 --> 01:22:12.390
All the soldiers had to leave

01:22:12.390 --> 01:22:14.670
so that they could go
fight other battles.

01:22:14.670 --> 01:22:19.000
So, they went to the
Kentucky School for the Deaf

01:22:19.000 --> 01:22:22.540
and they asked the children
there to help bury the dead.

01:22:22.540 --> 01:22:26.830
They said there were about 300
dead bodies after that battle.

01:22:26.830 --> 01:22:28.970
So, those children were
certainly not naïve at all,

01:22:28.970 --> 01:22:31.580 position:56%
they were very aware from their help

01:22:31.580 --> 01:22:36.160
in that situation of
death and dying.

01:22:36.160 --> 01:22:40.270
You know, also keep in mind that
there were a lot of deaf children

01:22:40.270 --> 01:22:44.920
who saw the deaths of their
fathers, brothers, friends,

01:22:44.920 --> 01:22:48.090
neighbors throughout the war.

01:22:54.220 --> 01:22:57.510
Let's talk a little bit more about
the National Literary Society

01:22:57.510 --> 01:23:00.500
for the Deaf and the context
of what I'm talking about here.

01:23:00.500 --> 01:23:03.630
As we mentioned before,
it was founded in 1907.

01:23:03.630 --> 01:23:07.530
And I thought that it was
an interesting coincidence

01:23:07.530 --> 01:23:09.230
that 40 years before that,

01:23:09.230 --> 01:23:12.950
many schools for the deaf had their
own literary societies embedded

01:23:12.950 --> 01:23:14.670
within the schools.

01:23:14.670 --> 01:23:18.480
So, one example of this is the
Kentucky School for the Deaf

01:23:18.480 --> 01:23:21.240
in which I found the
minutes from their meetings

01:23:21.240 --> 01:23:25.110
in a manuscript that's shown here.

01:23:25.110 --> 01:23:27.900
It's called "The Minute Book
of the Deaf Mute Society

01:23:27.900 --> 01:23:30.400
of the Kentucky Institution
for the Deaf and Dumb."

01:23:30.400 --> 01:23:32.490
So, I read through it.

01:23:32.490 --> 01:23:38.640 position:56%
And these kids were heavily involved
on a weekly basis in debates,

01:23:38.640 --> 01:23:43.200
debates on topics that were
really pertinent to the civil war.

01:23:43.200 --> 01:23:47.630
One question was, was
President Lincoln right

01:23:47.630 --> 01:23:51.940
in declaring war on
the seceding states?

01:23:54.130 --> 01:23:58.460
Another debate was on the
bombardment of Fort Henry.

01:23:58.460 --> 01:24:02.950 position:56%
And there were multiple other topics
that were found here in this book.

01:24:02.950 --> 01:24:08.180
And it certainly was not isolated
to the Kentucky School for the Deaf

01:24:08.180 --> 01:24:11.700
or to debate groups but
also to newspapers as well.

01:24:11.700 --> 01:24:15.410
The American School for the Deaf,
I'm sure you're all familiar

01:24:15.410 --> 01:24:19.610
with this, they-- celebrating
200 years coming

01:24:19.610 --> 01:24:22.510
up here pretty soon in 2018.

01:24:22.510 --> 01:24:27.960 position:56%
Some people are hoping that the post
[inaudible] is going to commemorate

01:24:27.960 --> 01:24:30.860
that anniversary with
a special stamp

01:24:30.860 --> 01:24:34.040
to honor the American
School for the Deaf.

01:24:34.040 --> 01:24:38.150
At any rate, ASD is a
very fascinating place.

01:24:38.150 --> 01:24:42.280
Before the war, there
were many abolitionists,

01:24:42.280 --> 01:24:47.670
people who opposed slavery
who were teachers at that ASD,

01:24:47.670 --> 01:24:55.200
including Thomas Hopkins Gallaudet,
Lewis Weld after him and so on.

01:24:55.200 --> 01:24:56.880
Edmund Booth was a
teacher there as well.

01:24:56.880 --> 01:25:01.480
So, the list of well-known
deaf names is quite long.

01:25:01.480 --> 01:25:07.620
The school had kids from the south
actually there before the war.

01:25:07.620 --> 01:25:14.260
And because there were
famous abolitionists in the--

01:25:14.260 --> 01:25:18.560
you know, on the teaching
staff or had been invited,

01:25:18.560 --> 01:25:26.930
Lewis Weld being one of them, was
surprised to find that deaf kinds

01:25:26.930 --> 01:25:33.640
in Hartford, Connecticut where
ASD is located really proved all

01:25:33.640 --> 01:25:39.470
of his beliefs on slavery, all of
his writings on slavery, you know,

01:25:39.470 --> 01:25:42.210
where obviously controversial
to southern children

01:25:42.210 --> 01:25:44.820
who had come from plantations.

01:25:44.820 --> 01:25:49.290
And so, the deaf northern
children had published articles

01:25:49.290 --> 01:25:52.570
that were supporting these
abolitionists' views and some

01:25:52.570 --> 01:25:56.740
of those actually included the
children from the southern states.

01:25:56.740 --> 01:25:59.960
Here's a newspaper for
the deaf community.

01:25:59.960 --> 01:26:02.620
And it talks about
"Boys in the Battle

01:26:02.620 --> 01:26:07.020
of Shiloh" and "The Dying Soldier".

01:26:07.020 --> 01:26:11.150
So again, schools for the deaf were
encouraging deaf schools to read

01:26:11.150 --> 01:26:13.820
about the war and to
write about it as well.

01:26:13.820 --> 01:26:16.040
This is coming from the North
Carolina School at Raleigh.

01:26:16.040 --> 01:26:23.920
Some teachers during the war who
were not involved during the war,

01:26:23.920 --> 01:26:26.390
continue to advocate
the deaf children

01:26:26.390 --> 01:26:27.970
to read about what was going on.

